While vacationing in the San Juan Islands between Victoria, B.C. and Washington state, we were watching a pod of Orca's when they began to hunt and chase something. As you can see, it became evident pretty quick that a little harbour porpoise (Phocoena phocoena) was on their dinner plans. They chased the poor guy to the surface, jumped over him and landed on him until it was over. As brutal as it was to watch, the Orca's have to eat. Some are fish eaters, some are marine mammal eaters. We found out what these were..

The killer whale or orca are a species of toothed whales belonging to the dolphin family. The largest member of the dolphin family and “one of the world’s most powerful predators”, the orca (scientific name Orcinus orca) is known to be an extremely intelligent mammalian species both socially and emotionally, with highly developed brains wired to navigate their expansive oceanic environment (“Animals: Orca” 2015). Immediately recognizable by their characteristic black and white colouring, orcas exist in very transient populations of family groupings called pods, swimming vast distances of the world’s oceans daily in search of prey. These great distances of travel mean they are more widely distributed than any other marine mammals (whales, dolphins or porpoises) in the world. Though found throughout all parts of the oceans, killer whales are found in higher populations in “cold waters, including Antarctica, the North Atlantic and Pacific oceans” (“Killer Whale (Orcinus orca)” 2017). They are also found at lower populations in tropical, subtropical and offshore waters. 
Generally, the orca spans from 23-32 feet in length, weighs up to 6 tons and has a life span of 50-100 years in the wild (Visser et al 2008). Due to a considerable variance in traits relating to sexual dimorphism, males and females tend to have different standard ranges of such traits. Males can reach a length of 32 feet, weigh up to 22 000 pounds (10 000 kg) and have a typical lifespan of 30 years, but can live as long as 50-60 years. In contrast, females can reach 28 feet in length, weigh up to 16 500 pounds (7 500 kg) and have a typical lifespan of 50 years, but can live as long as 100 years (“Killer Whale (Orcinus orca)” 2017). 
Diet in killer whales varies greatly between pods due to the fact that prey obtained is often population or geographic specific; however, all populations belong to the carnivorous trophic level. Three distinct populations among orcas have been recognized as 3 separate ecotypes: they are fish-eaters that remain in one general geographical area (resident orcas), flesh-eaters that roam widely throughout coastal regions (offshore orcas), and migrants of deep ocean waters (transient, or Bigg’s orcas) (Chadwick 2001). Fish-eating resident pods in the eastern North Pacific feed mainly on Chinook salmon, and other fish-eaters off the coast of Norway feed on herring or other schooling fish. Transient orcas in the eastern North Pacific feed on marine mammals, some of which include harbor seals, Dall’s porpoises, harbor porpoise, California sea lions, gray whale calves, and elephant seals (Berghan and Norton 2007). In waters off New Zealand, some orcas feed primarily on stingrays and sharks (Visser 2007). Different types of killer whales in Antarctic waters are known to feed off various prey: Type A orcas feed on minke whales; Type B orcas feed on seals; and Type C orcas feed on Antarctic toothfish and other various species of fish (“Killer Whale (Orcinus orca)” 2017).
Orca whales are highly social mammals whose social systems operate based on matriarchy. They remain in tight-knit pods of direct and closely-related family members (Visser et al 2008). Killer whales are polygynandrous meaning both males and females have multiple mates over the course of a season/lifetime (Burnett 2009). Orcas are very protective of their young and highly nurture their calves for up to 2 years after birth, and are cooperative breeders who help protect, feed and bring up the young in their pod whether they are biologically related or not. Males reach sexual maturity at 10-13 years of age, whereas females reach sexual maturity at 6-10 years of age (Burnett 2009). Breeding can occur at any time of the year, with females breeding every 3-10 years for an average 25-year period and birthing only a single calf at a time after a 12-18 month gestation period (Burnett 2009). It is estimated that female orcas breed for an average 25-year period. Orcas hunt in deadly pods containing up to 40 individuals where communication among members is crucial to the execution of effective hunting strategies (“Animals: Orca” 2015). They produce 3 categories of sounds: clicks, whistles and pulsed calls, all of which are used to orient themselves in space, for feeding and predation and to communicate with others (Berghan and Norton 2007). Echolocation clicks are thought to be used mainly for navigation and deciphering prey from surrounding objects in the environment, but are also frequently observed during social interactions (“Killer Whale (Orcinus orca)” 2017). Whistles and pulsed calls are believed to have communicative use in social settings. 
Killer whales are apex predators, meaning they reside “at the top of the marine food chain” and have no natural predators (Burnett 2009). However, younger orcas are at risk of being attacked by other killer whales or sharks. Orcas have never been extensively hunted by humans in their natural habitat, though live capture for aquarium display and the culling of orca fish prey have exerted pressures on killer whale niches in the past. Orcas currently remain on Appendix II of the CITES (the Convention on International Trade in Endangered Species of Wild Fauna and Flora) official site, meaning they are not threatened by extinction, but “conservation efforts must be employed to help keep them from moving closer to extinction” (Burnett 2009). Killer whales have not been as effected by human exploitation as have other species of marine mammals and whales. 
Did you know? The great white shark stands no chance against the killer whale. Being the largest apex predator that is also known to feed on baby blue whales, baby sperm whales and even polar bears if the opportunity arises, a pod of orcas will encircle a shark and swim rapidly in one direction around the shark to form an underwater whirlpool, causing the shark to assume a belly-up position (Berghan and Norton 2007). Sharks need to be in constant motion in order for their gills to extract the oxygen from the moving water, so when they are stationary in this position they become oxygen-deprived and are much easier to take down (Chadwick 2001). This group hunting allows orcas to have a high success rate when pursuing prey.

I observed this pod of at least three orcas from Four Mile Rock in the Magnolia neighborhood of Seattle. They were gradualling moving south but spent quite a bit of time in this area moving back and forth. 

At several points, one Orca lifted its heads straight out of the water to eye a passing cargo ship. There was also some tail slapping.

description: Heard there are orcas around the islands. Grabbed a 400mm telezoom lens and headed over. Launched the kayak and starting scanning the horizon while enjoying the kelp forests. Then heard a breath and saw this thing right behind me. It was too close for a tele lens. So while I struggled switching to a normal lens, it came by, slowed down under the kayak, made eye contact, and then proceeded to swim away. I managed to get a shot of its rear, right in front of the kayak.

Near Obstruction Island, aboard the vessel Island Explorer, we encountered a family of Bigg's orcas.  This group is led by 46-year-old matriarch Hutchins (T100). Traveling with her was her 23-year-old son Laurel (T100C), and her 11-year-old daughter Estrella (T100f).
Traveling from Obstruction Island to East Sound aboard the vessel Island Explorer.  This is a member of the T100 family of Bigg's Orcas.

In East Sound. aboard the vessel Island Explorer.  The Bigg's with the remarkably tall dorsal fin is the 23-year-old male Laurel (T100C).  Other fins in these shots are the 46-year-old matriarch Hutchins (T100), and her 11-year-old daughter Estrella (T100F).
